Gods and Goddesses

- the ancient Romans were polytheistic, meaning they believed in multiple gods

Vesta

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Sister of Jupiter
- Goddess of the hearth
- Protector of home and family
- One of the first gods worshipped

Janus

- watched over Roman houses
- shown with two faces
- hung over every doorway
- month of January is named for him

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)Saturn

- God of seeds and planting (agriculture)
- He also associated with wealth
- The celebration of Saturnalia was held in December to celebrate him; there were feasts, gift-giving, and games

The Punic Wars

**1st Punic War**

- Rome vs. Carthage
- Carthage had many ships, while Rome had none
- Lasted for 23 years
- Rome won and took over Carthage

# 2nd Punic War

- Hannibal from Carthage held a grudge
- He crossed the Alps and had elephants, which the Romans had never seen before
- After many losses on both sides, Carthage and Rome signed a peace treaty
- Carthage had to give up Spain and pay a lot of money to Rome

**3rd Punic War**

- Fought against Hannibal
- Only lasted 3 years
- Rome destroyed Carthage and poured salt in the soil so no crops could grow

Important Romans

# Julius Caesar

- Ruled Rome for 5 years
- Killed by the Senate
- After his death, there was a civil war

# Augustus Caesar (Octavian)

- Changed his name from Octavian to Augustus (meaning respected one)
- Was Julius Caesar’s great nephew and adopted son

# Nero

- Believed himself to be a great muscian
- Rumored to have started a fire in Rome

Entertainment

Colosseum: a grand amphitheater (stadium) in Rome where games and competitons were held

- gladiator vs. gladiator
- gladiator vs. animal/the hunts
- animal vs. animal

Circus Maximus: where chariot and boat races were held

Pompeii and Mount Vesuvius

- Mt. Vesuvius erupted in AD79
- Ash and pumice (volcanic rock) and hot gas from Mt. Vesuvius covered Pompeii. The town and those who could not escape were

buried.

Romans and Christians

- Emperors ruled Rome for 500 years after Augustus Caesar
- Romans thought Christians were dangerous to Rome because they worshipped one god instead of all Roman gods
- Constantine: made Christianity the official religion of Rome
- B.C. = Before Christ
- A.D. = In the Year of Our Lord

Decline of the Roman Empire

There were many theories to explain why the Roman Empire fell apart.

# Military

- poor pay
- Roman soldiers pillaging

# Economic

- heavy taxes on people
- slavery slowed new inventions

# Social

- less belief in hard work
- no one helped poor

# Political

- bad emperors
- empire split into East and West

**Justinian code:** Roman laws that were written and saved
